NLP Module Project Solution¶

Problem Statement¶

Business Context¶

The prices of the stocks of companies listed under a global exchange are influenced by a variety of factors, with the company's financial performance, innovations and collaborations, and market sentiment being factors that play a significant role. News and media reports can rapidly affect investor perceptions and, consequently, stock prices in the highly competitive financial industry. With the sheer volume of news and opinions from a wide variety of sources, investors and financial analysts often struggle to stay updated and accurately interpret its impact on the market. As a result, investment firms need sophisticated tools to analyze market sentiment and integrate this information into their investment strategies.

Problem Defintion¶

An investment startup has collected historical daily news for a specific company listed under NASDAQ, along with data on its daily stock price and trade volumes.

We have to analyze the data, develop an AI-driven sentiment analysis system that will automatically process and analyze news articles to gauge market sentiment, and summarizing the news at a weekly level to enhance the accuracy of their stock price predictions and optimize investment strategies.

This will empower their financial analysts with actionable insights, leading to more informed investment decisions and improved client outcomes.

Data Dictionary¶

  • Date: The date the news was released
  • News: The content of news articles that could potentially affect the company's stock price
  • Open The stock price (in $) at the beginning of the day
  • High: The highest stock price (in $) reached during the day
  • Low: The lowest stock price (in $) reached during the day
  • Close: The adjusted stock price (in $) at the end of the day
  • Volume: The number of shares traded during the day
  • Label: The sentiment polarity of the news content
    • 1: Positive
    • 0: Neutral
    • -1: Negative

    '''
      Draw the histogram and box plot for the given column
      in the given dataframe

    '''

    fig,(ax1,ax2) = plt.subplots(1,2,figsize=(10,3))


    plt.suptitle(f'Distribution of {col} ')

    if format == True:
      ax1.xaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(format_millions))
      ax2.xaxis.set_major_formatter(FuncFormatter(format_millions))


def label_legends(ax):
    '''
      Add the legends to the given axis
    '''

    L = ax.legend(loc='upper right')
    L.get_texts()[0].set_text('Negative')
    L.get_texts()[1].set_text('Neutral')
    L.get_texts()[2].set_text('Positive')

def format_millions(value, tick_number):
    '''
      Format the tick value in millions

    '''
    return f'{int(value / 1000000)}M'

# defining a function to remove special characters
def remove_special_characters(text):
    # Defining the regex pattern to match non-alphanumeric characters
    pattern = '[^A-Za-z0-9]+'

    # Finding the specified pattern and replacing non-alphanumeric characters with a blank string
    new_text = ''.join(re.sub(pattern, ' ', text))

    return new_text

# defining a function to remove stop words using the NLTK library
def remove_stopwords(text):
    # Split text into separate words
    words = text.split()

    # Removing English language stopwords
    new_text = ' '.join([word for word in words if word not in stopwords.words('english')])

    return new_text
In [29]:

In [30]:
# Loading the Porter Stemmer
ps = PorterStemmer()

# defining a function to perform stemming
def apply_porter_stemmer(text):
    # Split text into separate words
    words = text.split()

    # Applying the Porter Stemmer on every word of a message and joining the stemmed words back into a single string
    new_text = ' '.join([ps.stem(word) for word in words])

    return new_text
In [31]:
# Applying the function to perform stemming
df['Final_Cleaned_News'] = df['Cleaned_News_No_Stopwords'].apply(apply_porter_stemmer)

In [36]:
def average_vectorizer_Word2Vec(doc):
    # Initializing a feature vector for the news
    feature_vector = np.zeros((vec_size,), dtype="float64")

    # Creating a list of words in the news that are present in the model vocabulary
    words_in_vocab = [word for word in doc.split() if word in words]

    # adding the vector representations of the words
    for word in words_in_vocab:
        feature_vector += np.array(word_vector_dict[word])

    # Dividing by the number of words to get the average vector
    if len(words_in_vocab) != 0:
        feature_vector /= len(words_in_vocab)

    return feature_vector

Sentiment Analysis¶

Approach and Metric Selection¶

We need to build a base model that can use the embedding data created above and predict the Sentiment - Label (Positive,Neutral,Negative) Of these are we are more interessted in the minority classes - Positive and Negative

  • Split Data: For each type of embedding, we will split into Train, Validation and Test sets
  • Base Model: Random Forest Classifier against all 3 embeddings
  • Hyperparameter tuning: GridSearch CV with Stratified K-Fold for 5 folds
  • Metric: Considering the dataset imbalanced containing 48% of majority class, we will use F1 Score as the evaluating metric

Helper Methods¶

def clf_model_performance(y_true,y_preds,y_probs):

    '''
        Calculates the accuracy,precision, recall
        and f1 score and roc_auc for the given model against the true values
        and predictions provided.

        Returns: the metrics stored as a Pandas dataframe

    '''

    acc = accuracy_score(y_true,y_preds)
    precision = precision_score(y_true,y_preds,average='macro')
    recall = recall_score(y_true,y_preds,average='macro')
    f1 = f1_score(y_true,y_preds,average='macro')
    roc_auc = roc_auc_score(y_true,y_probs,multi_class='ovr',average='macro')


    metrics_df = pd.DataFrame(
        {'Accuracy':acc,
         'Precision':precision,
         'Recall':recall,
         'F1 Score':f1,
         'AUC ROC':roc_auc},
    index=[0])

    return metrics_df
In [49]:
def clf_grid_search(model,param_grid):

    '''
        Performs Hyper Parameter tuning using sklearn GridSearchCV
        for the given model and parameter grid using 5 fold Cross Validation

        param_grid is a dictionary where keys are the parameter names
        for the given model and the values are list of possible values that
        need to be considered for the tuning

        Prints the Best Score and Parameters combination

        Returns: the best estimator as a result of GridSearchCV

    '''
    # use Stratified KFold CV with 5 folds
    skf = StratifiedKFold(n_splits=5)
    grid_search = GridSearchCV(estimator=model, param_grid=param_grid,
                          cv=skf, n_jobs=-1, verbose=2, scoring='accuracy')

    grid_search.fit(X_train, y_train)

    print('*'*70)
    print(f'Best Score: {grid_search.best_score_}')
    print('*'*70)
    print('Best parameters:')
    print(grid_search.best_params_)


    return grid_search.best_estimator_

def model_train(model_label,X_train, y_train,X_valid,y_valid,param_grid=None):

    '''
        Helper method that will define and tune a RF for the given
        train and validation set. Parameters are tuned using GridSearchCV against
        the given param grid

    '''

    #define a base RF Classifier and fit it
    #using entropy for imbaclanced dataset
    rf_model = RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=50, criterion = 'entropy', random_state=42)
    rf_model.fit(X_train, y_train)

    #make predictions and probabilities on both train and validation set
    y_preds_train = rf_model.predict(X_train)
    y_preds = rf_model.predict(X_valid)


    y_probs_train = rf_model.predict_proba(X_train)
    y_probs = rf_model.predict_proba(X_valid)

    #calculate various performance metrics on base model
    train_df = clf_model_performance(y_train,y_preds_train,y_probs_train)
    valid_df = clf_model_performance(y_valid,y_preds,y_probs)

    print(f'{model_label} Base Training classification report\n')
    print(classification_report(y_train,y_preds_train))
    print('*'*70)
    print(f'{model_label} Base Validation classification report\n')
    print(classification_report(y_valid,y_preds))


    #Hyper param tuning and get the best model
    rf_clf_best = clf_grid_search(rf_model,param_grid)

    #make predictions and probabilities on both train and validation set
    #using the best tuned model
    y_preds_train = rf_clf_best.predict(X_train)
    y_preds = rf_clf_best.predict(X_valid)

    y_probs_train = rf_clf_best.predict_proba(X_train)
    y_probs = rf_clf_best.predict_proba(X_valid)

    #calculate various performance metrics on best model
    train_df_best = clf_model_performance(y_train,y_preds_train,y_probs_train)
    valid_df_best = clf_model_performance(y_valid,y_preds,y_probs)

    print('*'*70)
    print(f'{model_label} Best Training classification report\n')
    print(classification_report(y_train,y_preds_train))
    print('*'*70)
    print(f'{model_label} Best Validation classification report\n')
    print(classification_report(y_valid,y_preds))

    #create a dataframe summarising performance across base and best models
    #for the given embedding

    perf_df = pd.concat([train_df.T,valid_df.T,train_df_best.T,valid_df_best.T],axis=1)

    perf_df.columns = [
    f"{model_label} Base Train",
    f"{model_label} Base Valid",
    f"{model_label} Best Train",
    f"{model_label} Best Valid",
   ]

    return perf_df, rf_clf_best

Extract Summary¶

  • We will separate the weekly grouped data into postive and negative groups
  • Then we use the model loaded above to identify Top 3 News Topic and Event Summary for each section. This will be provided in JSON format from the model
  • We will convert the JSON output into different columns using Pandas json_normalise()
  • We will combine the weekly data for each sentiment set to get a dataframe that can display the Date, Top 3 Positive News Topics and Summary and Top 3 Negative News Topics
In [86]:
#define the prompt to generate the summary of topics in JSON format
prompt = '''

You are an expert data analyst specializing in news content analysis.

Task: Analyze the provided news headline and return the main topics contained within it.

Instructions:
1. Read the news headline carefully.
2. Identify the main subjects or entities mentioned in the headline.
3. Determine the key events or actions described in the headline.
4. Extract relevant keywords that represent the topics.
5. List the topics in a concise manner.

Return the output in JSON format with:
  - keys as the topic number and values as the actual topic
  - keys as the topic number suffixed with _Events and values as the relevant keywords for that topic
  - include atleast 1 topic and maximum of 3 topics only
  - Do not include any other text in the output except the JSON
  - use broader category of topic when in doubt


Sample output:
{"1": "Politics", "1_Events" : "trade talks between Beijing and Washington, European stock markets",
 "2": "Economy", "2_Events" :"gold prices, global economic slowdown, stock market volatility",
 "3": "Trade", "3_Events" : "U.S.-China trade war, OPEC" }

'''
In [87]:
#Defining the response function
def get_llm_response(prompt, news):
    model_output = lcpp_llm(
      f"""
      [INST]
      {prompt}
      News Articles: {news}
      [/INST]
      """,
      max_tokens=15024,
        temperature=0.01,
        top_p=0.95,
        repeat_penalty=1.2,
        top_k=3,
      echo=False,
    )

    final_output = model_output["choices"][0]["text"]

    return final_output
In [88]:
# defining a function to parse the JSON output from the model
def extract_json_data(json_str):
    import json
    try:
        # Find the indices of the opening and closing curly braces
        json_start = json_str.find('{')
        json_end = json_str.rfind('}')

        if json_start != -1 and json_end != -1:
            extracted_category = json_str[json_start:json_end + 1]  # Extract the JSON object
            data_dict = json.loads(extracted_category)
            return data_dict
        else:
            print(f"Warning: JSON object not found in response: {json_str}")
            return {}
    except json.JSONDecodeError as e:
        print(f"Error parsing JSON: {e}")
        return {}

#define function to extract suumary for weekly news
def extract_weekly_events(news):

    response = get_llm_response(prompt,news)
    json_data = extract_json_data(response)

    return json_data

Key Insights¶

  • Daily News affects both : stock price and volume of stocks sold per day
  • In general, News with Positive/Neutral sentiments lead to a higher stock price and higher volumes of sales as compared to news with negative sentiment
  • Using Supervised Machine Learning and NLP techniques, it is possible to predict the Sentiment of the news and thereby analyse its impact on stock price and stock volume
  • News related to Economy, Business, Technology, Trade tend to have a higher impact compared to categories like Entertainment/Politics in general
  • Post January month, less news are captured for all sentiments

Recommendations¶

  • Identify trustworthy and secure data sources from which news details can be obtained
  • Implement a pipeline to feed the news data in real time and perform sentiment analysis
  • Introduce a system that can detect and send alerts in case of any fake news is found in the system - this will minimise the adverse effects on stock trading
  • Introduce an alerting meachanism to identify if less news is flowing into the system - lack of news details will affect the sentiment prediction and its impact on stock price and sales
